## Implementation Requirements

### Frontend
- Architecture:
  - React (TypeScript) with a modular component library aligned to the design system
  - State management: React Query or SWR for data fetching; global state with context for user preferences
  - Hooks: useArraySafe hook patterns to ensure safe mapping over data (e.g., const safeList = Array.isArray(list) ? list : [])
- Components to build:
  - NotificationCenter: header, digest summary, per-event cards
  - DigestPanel: grouping of notifications by digest window
  - NotificationCard: icon, title, meta, action menu (Acknowledge, Snooze, View)
  - ApprovalsQueueView: list, diff panel, rationale, decision controls
  - MasterDashboardWidgets: cron snapshot, alerts, search bar, quick command bar
  - TemplatesEditor: template editor with localization keys and variable placeholders
  - SettingsKiosk: channel toggles, digest rules, snooze rules
  - Toasts/Modals for actions and confirmations
- Data safety:
  - All arrays and API responses must be guarded: (data ?? []) and Array.isArray checks
  - Initialize useState for arrays: useState<MyType[]>([])
  - Optional chaining for nested API responses: apiResponse?.payload?.items
  - Destructure with defaults: const { items = [], count = 0 } = response ?? {}
- Accessibility:
  - ARIA labels, keyboard navigation, and semantic HTML
- Localization:
  - i18n ready; templates with placeholders; locale-aware rendering
- Performance:
  - Pagination or virtualization for long notification lists
  - Debounced search; minimize re-renders

### Backend
- APIs and microservices:
  - Notification Service: multi-channel dispatcher
  - Digest Scheduler: cron-based or window-based digest bundling
  - Template Service: localization and rendering
  - Email Service: SendGrid integration with status/webhook handling
  - Push Service: FCM integration with token management
  - Approvals Service: queue management, rationale management, conditional approvals
  - Cronjobs Service: schedule creation/updates, trigger logic, input payloads, constraints, safety rails, retry policy
- Data models (MSSQL/Postgres or chosen DB):
  - users(id, email, locale, timezone, preferences JSONB, push_tokens JSONB, ... )
  - notifications(id, user_id, channel, template_id, payload JSONB, status, digest_id, created_at, persisted_at, read_at, snoozed_until, retry_count, last_error)
  - digests(id, user_id, window_start, window_end, delivered_at, status)
  - templates(id, name, locale, subject, body, variables JSONB, last_modified)
  - channels(user_id, in_app, email, push, digest_enabled, digest_frequency, quiet_hours)
  - approvals_queue(id, cronjob_id, requestor_id, rationale, status, comments, created_at, updated_at, diff_blob)
  - cronjobs(id, name, enabled, schedule_expression, timezone, trigger_type, target, input_payload JSONB, permissions, constraints JSONB, safety_rails JSONB, retry_policy JSONB, outputs JSONB, next_run_at, last_run_at, last_run_status)
  - audit_logs(id, user_id, action, object_type, object_id, metadata JSONB, timestamp)
- Business logic:
  - Per-user digest batching with respect to timezone and locale
  - Retry/backoff policies with dead-letter routing
  - Template rendering with variable substitution and localization
  - Validation: strict schema validation for all API inputs
  - Security: enforce authentication and authorization; restrict access to users based on roles
- Validation:
  - All API responses validated; e.g., const list = Array.isArray(response?.data) ? response.data : []
- Data safety:
  - nullish checks for all optional fields; guard against null data in all endpoints

### Integration
- Data flow orchestration:
  - Event sources (run outcomes, anomalies, scheduled cron actions) push to Notification Engine
  - Engine enriches events with user preferences and templates, then dispatches via channels
  - Digest Scheduler batches events per user and sends digest notifications
  - Alerts feed Approvals Queue when approvals are required
  - Master Dashboard queries consolidated statuses and surfacing alerts
- Consistency:
  - All modules use consistent data structures for notifications and digests
  - Central audit logs for all user actions and system events
- Security and compliance:
  - OAuth2/JWT authentication; role-based access for Approvals, Settings, and Master Dashboard
  - Data access controls per tenant/account
- Observability:
  - Centralized logging and metrics for delivery success/failure, retries, digest generation, and snoozes
  - Tracing across agent-to-agent messages in cronjobs

---

## User Experience Flow

1) User Preference Setup
- User visits Settings > Notifications
- Configures channels: in-app, email, push
- Sets per-channel preferences: digest frequency, quiet hours, retry limits
- Creates localization preferences (default locale) and template defaults

2) Event Occurrence
- An event occurs (run outcome, anomaly, or approval requirement)
- Notification Engine evaluates user preferences and creates notification payloads
- If digest mode is enabled, event is queued for digest window; otherwise immediate delivery

3) Delivery & Snooze
- Notification is dispatched to all subscribed channels
- User receives in-app banner/toast, email, and/or push notification
- User can Snooze or Acknowledge from in-app notification
- Snooze defers delivery for a configured window; snoozed items appear in digest or re-delivery

4) Approvals Queue (for scheduled cron actions)
- Cronjob scheduled requests appear in Approvals Queue with diffs and agent rationale
- Approver reviews details, optionally adds comments, and decides Approve/Reject
- Conditional approvals may trigger alternate flows
- Approved actions proceed; rejected actions generate notes and audit trails

5) Master Dashboard Interaction
- User uses global search to locate notifications, cronjobs, or approvals
- Quick command bar enables rapid actions (e.g., pause digest, reschedule cron)
- Active cronjobs snapshot shows next run times and recent outcomes
- Cross-module alerts are surfaced with status chips and trend indicators

6) Templates & Templates Editor
- User edits templates with placeholders and localization keys
- Preview renders sample data for current locale
- Saving updates templates, affecting future deliveries

7) Admin/Settings
- Admin configures channel capabilities, template mappings, and digest rules
- Any change propagates to subsequent notification deliveries and templates

